1
00:00:29,594 --> 00:00:31,422
Hi.

2
00:00:31,553 --> 00:00:34,121
I'm Morgan Freeman.

3
00:00:34,251 --> 00:00:36,688
You know, Paul robeson,
the great singer and activist,

4
00:00:36,819 --> 00:00:41,345
used to sing a song called
"scandalize my name."

5
00:00:41,476 --> 00:00:46,307
Ironically, because of the red
scare during the cold war,

6
00:00:46,437 --> 00:00:50,137
that song came
to define his life,

7
00:00:50,267 --> 00:00:53,140
because his name along with
that of many other performers,

8
00:00:53,270 --> 00:00:57,796
was scandalized by what came
to be known as mccarthyism.

9
00:00:57,927 --> 00:01:00,582
Now, black performers were
particularly vulnerable

10
00:01:00,712 --> 00:01:05,152
because we had just begun
to be taken seriously.

11
00:01:05,282 --> 00:01:09,417
And any outspokenness
against racism

12
00:01:09,547 --> 00:01:13,334
was seen as the work
of communist agitators.

13
00:01:13,421 --> 00:01:15,510
Many of the performers
you will see in this film

14
00:01:15,640 --> 00:01:17,729
you may not recognize.

15
00:01:17,816 --> 00:01:22,169
Goes to show how blacklisting
could make people disappear.

16
00:01:22,299 --> 00:01:27,391
A group of former FBI agents,
with hoover's support,

17
00:01:27,522 --> 00:01:31,526
put together this book
"red channels,"

18
00:01:31,656 --> 00:01:33,093
which claims to be a list

19
00:01:33,223 --> 00:01:37,271
of all the members of the
broadcast entertainment industry

20
00:01:37,358 --> 00:01:39,795
who had communist affiliations.

21
00:01:39,925 --> 00:01:41,623
"Red channels"
became so successful

22
00:01:41,710 --> 00:01:43,973
that other groups
formed their own lists,

23
00:01:44,104 --> 00:01:46,454
so the blacklist grew.

24
00:01:46,584 --> 00:01:48,499
And the only way you could tell
you were on this list

25
00:01:48,630 --> 00:01:53,156
is if you didn't get any work
and people shunned you.

26
00:01:53,287 --> 00:01:57,943
And perhaps worst of all
was the slander of your name

27
00:01:58,030 --> 00:02:02,513
and of the causes
you believed in.

28
00:02:02,644 --> 00:02:08,824
Reading this book today is like
an honor roll of entertainers,

29
00:02:08,954 --> 00:02:10,608
people in the industry,

30
00:02:10,739 --> 00:02:15,396
who had the courage
and enough care

31
00:02:15,526 --> 00:02:21,228
to lend their name
and talents to help others.

32
00:02:21,358 --> 00:02:24,970
When the film begins, of course,
we're in a happier time.

33
00:02:25,057 --> 00:02:27,321
Late '30s and early '40s,

34
00:02:27,408 --> 00:02:30,019
people were trucking up
to Harlem

35
00:02:30,150 --> 00:02:32,152
looking for a bright future.

36
00:02:32,282 --> 00:02:33,501
If you were an actor
you might try

37
00:02:33,631 --> 00:02:36,112
to get into dick Campbell's
Rose mclendon players

38
00:02:36,199 --> 00:02:40,247
or Frederick O'Neal's
American negro theater.

39
00:02:40,377 --> 00:02:41,770
Though ten years later,

40
00:02:41,857 --> 00:02:44,033
both O'Neal and Campbell
were blacklisted for demanding

41
00:02:44,164 --> 00:02:47,906
better representation
for blacks on television.

42
00:02:48,037 --> 00:02:52,172
But when our story begins,
Harlem was the place to be.

43
00:02:55,044 --> 00:02:56,524
I can remember the time when,

44
00:02:56,611 --> 00:03:00,702
from 110th street
to 155th street,

45
00:03:00,832 --> 00:03:03,444
on 7th Avenue,

46
00:03:03,574 --> 00:03:06,577
it was called Harlem's Broadway

47
00:03:06,664 --> 00:03:10,712
and white people on Sunday
morning would come up there,

48
00:03:10,842 --> 00:03:12,583
and drive very slowly

49
00:03:12,714 --> 00:03:16,108
because that was the day
when all of the colored people,

50
00:03:16,239 --> 00:03:19,590
all of US,
were dressed to the nines.

51
00:03:19,721 --> 00:03:23,028
I mean to the nines,
with the gloves, with the veil,

52
00:03:23,115 --> 00:03:26,380
with the earrings,
with your best Sunday dress

53
00:03:26,467 --> 00:03:28,773
and people who lived
on that Avenue

54
00:03:28,904 --> 00:03:32,342
would look out and say
"here they come a'struttin."

55
00:03:32,473 --> 00:03:35,389
There's something of
an institution in Harlem

56
00:03:35,519 --> 00:03:40,611
in the days
when I came along, about 1928.

57
00:03:40,742 --> 00:03:42,265
It's called the tree of hope.

58
00:03:42,396 --> 00:03:44,267
There was actually a tree

59
00:03:44,398 --> 00:03:50,012
on the corner of 131st street
and 7th Avenue in Harlem.

60
00:03:50,142 --> 00:03:53,668
Those were the days when
you walked by the Lafayette,

61
00:03:53,798 --> 00:03:55,452
where all the beautiful,

62
00:03:55,583 --> 00:04:00,065
wonderful talented artists
would be standing between shows,

63
00:04:00,196 --> 00:04:02,024
underneath the tree of hope.

64
00:04:02,154 --> 00:04:03,504
And it was once said that

65
00:04:03,591 --> 00:04:05,506
they could cast any black show
they wanted to cast

66
00:04:05,636 --> 00:04:09,249
by coming up to 131st street
and 7th Avenue in Harlem

67
00:04:09,379 --> 00:04:11,599
and they'd find all the black
actors that they wanted,

68
00:04:11,729 --> 00:04:13,818
right there under
the tree of hope.

69
00:04:13,949 --> 00:04:16,081
So that's where we stood,
under the tree of hope,

70
00:04:16,212 --> 00:04:19,302
hoping that some white producer
would come uptown

71
00:04:19,389 --> 00:04:21,609
and would hire some of US
to go downtown.

72
00:04:21,739 --> 00:04:25,439
Ms. Lenoire:
If you were out of work all you
did was walk across the street,

73
00:04:25,569 --> 00:04:27,049
right in the middle
of the street,

74
00:04:27,136 --> 00:04:28,964
put your hand there
and make your wish

75
00:04:29,051 --> 00:04:32,881
and sure enough you'd get a job
the next week or something.

76
00:04:33,011 --> 00:04:38,756
In 1936 I came to New York

77
00:04:38,887 --> 00:04:41,846
and there my first work
was with dick Campbell

78
00:04:41,977 --> 00:04:46,242
and his particular group there,
the Rose mclendon players.

79
00:04:46,329 --> 00:04:53,380
On the 23rd of April in 1939
I arrived in New York.

80
00:04:53,510 --> 00:04:56,731
On that Monday I went and found
the Rose mclendon players,

81
00:04:56,861 --> 00:05:00,865
dick Campbell was on stage
nailing something

82
00:05:00,996 --> 00:05:02,737
and I asked him if I could join.

83
00:05:02,824 --> 00:05:06,044
I was nailing scenery and
standing up, my back was to him.

84
00:05:06,131 --> 00:05:08,612
He came in and he said
"mister Campbell?"

85
00:05:08,743 --> 00:05:10,005
I said "yes."

86
00:05:10,135 --> 00:05:13,704
He said "may I join
your theater group?"

87
00:05:13,835 --> 00:05:16,838
I said "well, with a voice
like that I would say yes."

88
00:05:16,968 --> 00:05:19,362
And I turned around
and looked to see who it was,

89
00:05:19,493 --> 00:05:21,930
and here was this long, tall,
skinny looking fellow,

90
00:05:22,060 --> 00:05:23,758
he looked very hungry.

91
00:05:23,888 --> 00:05:27,501
I said "you want to be
in the theater?"

92
00:05:27,631 --> 00:05:30,068
He said "yes, sir."

93
00:05:30,199 --> 00:05:32,157
When I came out of the Navy

94
00:05:32,288 --> 00:05:34,203
I became a building
superintendent,

95
00:05:34,334 --> 00:05:37,032
assistant to a building
superintendent.

96
00:05:37,162 --> 00:05:41,384
And while doing the repairs
in an apartment

97
00:05:41,515 --> 00:05:44,344
for one of the tenants,

98
00:05:44,474 --> 00:05:49,958
I had been given two tickets
as a gratuity to attend

99
00:05:50,088 --> 00:05:54,223
a performance at a place called
the American negro theater.

100
00:05:54,310 --> 00:05:56,443
I learned about
the American negro theater

101
00:05:56,530 --> 00:05:59,707
from an elevator operator

102
00:05:59,837 --> 00:06:02,623
in the building
that I was living in.

103
00:06:02,753 --> 00:06:04,886
He said "why don't you go over
there and try to find out

104
00:06:04,973 --> 00:06:07,410
if there isn't something you can
do because in those shows

105
00:06:07,541 --> 00:06:10,544
you don't have to sing and dance
like in these other shows.

106
00:06:10,674 --> 00:06:12,981
You don't have to act
dumb and stupid,

107
00:06:13,111 --> 00:06:14,635
carrying a tray and whatnot."

108
00:06:14,765 --> 00:06:16,550
I didn't care what I had to do.

109
00:06:16,680 --> 00:06:19,074
I just wanted to be
in the environment.

110
00:06:19,204 --> 00:06:20,467
I found it very stimulating.

111
00:06:20,597 --> 00:06:23,252
I found that
there was an intellect,

112
00:06:23,383 --> 00:06:34,089
that there was a scholarship,
there was purpose.

113
00:06:34,176 --> 00:06:37,658
And I was looking for purpose
and I thought this would be

114
00:06:37,788 --> 00:06:39,616
a very good place
in which to start.

115
