♪ All through the night, ♪

122
00:07:54,169 --> 00:08:05,528
♪ let it shine, let it shine,
let it shine. ♪

123
00:08:16,626 --> 00:08:21,022
I came out of the service
with great expectations.

124
00:08:21,109 --> 00:08:24,939
That we had just
defeated fascism,

125
00:08:25,069 --> 00:08:27,898
we had just defeated
totalitarianism,

126
00:08:28,029 --> 00:08:33,774
we had just defeated philosophy
of white supremacy.

127
00:08:33,904 --> 00:08:39,519
The world was in a mood
of great rejoicing.

128
00:08:39,649 --> 00:08:41,912
One of the things
that impressed me most

129
00:08:42,043 --> 00:08:44,785
about the New York
theatrical scene

130
00:08:44,872 --> 00:08:46,526
when I came back from the war,

131
00:08:46,656 --> 00:08:50,878
was an awareness
on everybody's part that the war

132
00:08:51,008 --> 00:08:57,101
had been a serious challenge
on the subject of race.

133
00:08:57,232 --> 00:09:04,021
We were all still shocked
at what had happened in Europe

134
00:09:04,152 --> 00:09:10,941
to the millions of Jews
and others in those camps.

135
00:09:11,072 --> 00:09:15,032
I'd expected that america
would be open and generous

136
00:09:15,163 --> 00:09:21,909
and rewarding to
its black citizens

137
00:09:22,039 --> 00:09:25,390
who had served in that war
and had served with great honor.

138
00:09:25,521 --> 00:09:27,088
There seemed to be
a determination

139
00:09:27,175 --> 00:09:31,179
immediately after the war
to say to ourselves

140
00:09:31,309 --> 00:09:33,181
"that would never happen again"

141
00:09:33,311 --> 00:09:37,402
that on the subject of race,
we were one, we were equal

142
00:09:37,533 --> 00:09:39,622
and we were partners
and brothers.

143
00:09:39,753 --> 00:09:41,755
When we came back there were
many forces in america,

144
00:09:41,885 --> 00:09:43,365
very powerful,

145
00:09:43,495 --> 00:09:46,324
that decided that those of US
who had been brainwashed

146
00:09:46,411 --> 00:09:48,239
with these new ideas
from the war,

147
00:09:48,370 --> 00:09:49,632
that thought we could come back

148
00:09:49,719 --> 00:09:51,808
and change the way america
was doing business

149
00:09:51,939 --> 00:09:57,161
was in for a very cruel
and a huge surprise.

150
00:09:57,292 --> 00:10:04,995
We were going to go back
to conditions as was before.

151
00:10:05,126 --> 00:10:08,520
We were to be a bunch of niggers
who were to come back

152
00:10:08,651 --> 00:10:12,220
and get those thoughts of
freedom out of our heads.

153
00:10:12,350 --> 00:10:16,572
We were seriously concerned that
america be a different place,

154
00:10:16,703 --> 00:10:18,705
as far as race was concerned.

155
00:10:18,835 --> 00:10:22,622
And that gave US a common
objective that was bigger,

156
00:10:22,752 --> 00:10:24,841
even than the parts
we were playing.

157
00:10:24,972 --> 00:10:29,411
Broadway had a kind of social
as well as a cultural function,

158
00:10:29,541 --> 00:10:31,587
which we took quite seriously.

159
00:10:31,718 --> 00:10:34,111
At the end of
a performance every night,

160
00:10:34,198 --> 00:10:37,114
somebody would say "hey let's
go over to so and so's,

161
00:10:37,245 --> 00:10:40,683
they're raising funds
to defend Willy McGee"

162
00:10:40,814 --> 00:10:43,425
or somebody had been lynched
in the south

163
00:10:43,555 --> 00:10:45,340
or some atrocity had happened.

164
00:10:45,470 --> 00:10:50,693
We made it our business to
become part of any force

165
00:10:50,824 --> 00:10:55,045
that was speaking out
against this inhumane cruelty.

166
00:10:55,176 --> 00:10:57,613
Mr. Davis: And we were
determined to force the issue

167
00:10:57,744 --> 00:11:01,051
of justice for everybody
onto the public consciousness.

168
00:11:01,182 --> 00:11:03,401
And the total theatrical
community, in my mind,

169
00:11:03,532 --> 00:11:04,968
seemed to be caught up in that.

170
00:11:05,099 --> 00:11:07,014
The producers were involved,
the directors, the actors,

171
00:11:07,144 --> 00:11:08,537
the writers.

172
00:11:08,668 --> 00:11:12,323
We belonged to a sort of
a blessed confraternity.

173
00:11:12,454 --> 00:11:14,064
And we were glad to be comrades

174
00:11:14,195 --> 00:11:18,765
and marching forward
in the same struggle.

175
00:11:18,895 --> 00:11:20,767
We didn't know how thoroughly
we were being watched.

176
00:11:20,897 --> 00:11:25,597
Certainly not in '46, '47, '48.

177
00:11:25,685 --> 00:11:31,734
All of a sudden
there emerged this...

178
00:11:31,865 --> 00:11:38,915
...this noise that erupted,

179
00:11:39,046 --> 00:11:44,965
this group that started
the talk about any and all of US

180
00:11:45,052 --> 00:11:49,752
who dared to embark on such
conduct were unpatriotic

181
00:11:49,883 --> 00:11:53,887
and were working towards
the worst interests of our home,

182
00:11:54,017 --> 00:11:57,934
our patriotism was to be
seriously challenged

183
00:11:58,065 --> 00:12:03,331
and some of US listened
to these utterances

184
00:12:03,461 --> 00:12:07,335
with complete disbelief.

185
00:12:07,465 --> 00:12:11,731
As a matter of fact it was a
huge stretch of the imagination

186
00:12:11,861 --> 00:12:13,341
to suggest that those of US

187
00:12:13,428 --> 00:12:16,997
who had struggled against
racism and oppression, sexism,

188
00:12:17,127 --> 00:12:21,697
and all the things we struggled
against were unpatriotic.

189
00:12:21,784 --> 00:12:27,050
When in fact we knew
and felt righteously strong.

190
00:12:27,224 --> 00:12:31,925
♪ There's an old man
called the Mississippi, ♪

191
00:12:32,099 --> 00:12:37,321
♪ that's the old man
I don't like to be. ♪

192
00:12:37,408 --> 00:12:41,935
♪ What does he care
if the world's got troubles? ♪

193
00:12:42,109 --> 00:12:50,465
♪ What does he care
if the land ain't free? ♪

194
00:12:50,639 --> 00:12:57,820
♪ Old man river,
that old man river, ♪

195
00:12:57,994 --> 00:13:04,000
♪ he must know something
but don't say nothin'. ♪

196
00:13:04,174 --> 00:13:13,749
♪ He just keeps rolling,
he keeps on rolling along. ♪

197
00:13:13,880 --> 00:13:20,712
My experience with Paul robeson
was on more levels than one.

198
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:26,327
On the personal level,
he was an immediate mentor

199
00:13:26,457 --> 00:13:30,548
and hero for those of US
in the theater,

200
00:13:30,679 --> 00:13:33,682
who wanted to be actors.

201
00:13:33,813 --> 00:13:36,772
We wanted to be,
to some degree, like he was.

202
00:13:36,903 --> 00:13:39,949
He was huge, he was beautiful,
he could sing,

203
00:13:40,080 --> 00:13:43,344
and he was an athlete,
and he was sexy.

204
00:13:43,474 --> 00:13:47,478
He had all of the positive
things that a young man

205
00:13:47,609 --> 00:13:50,830
and a young woman
could be inspired by.

206
00:13:50,960 --> 00:13:53,006
Paul represented to US

207
00:13:53,093 --> 00:13:57,314
that top moment,
the top possibility.

208
00:13:57,445 --> 00:13:59,708
An artist in every sense
of the word

209
00:13:59,839 --> 00:14:03,190
but his art was not only
an expression of his own talent

210
00:14:03,277 --> 00:14:04,713
or his love for beauty,

211
00:14:04,844 --> 00:14:10,980
it was his expression of
concern for the rest of US.

212
00:14:11,067 --> 00:14:14,592
The artist was the nurturer,
the artist was the defender,

213
00:14:14,723 --> 00:14:16,986
the artist was the spokesperson.

214
00:14:17,117 --> 00:14:21,208
He helped me interpret song,
he inspired me,

215
00:14:21,338 --> 00:14:24,167
he gave me a platform
in which to learn,

216
00:14:24,298 --> 00:14:29,433
to understand much about human
conduct and human affairs.

217
00:14:29,564 --> 00:14:38,921
His sensitivity, his honor,
his honesty, his compassion,

218
00:14:39,052 --> 00:14:45,058
all played a huge role
in how I perceived

219
00:14:45,188 --> 00:14:48,931
art and artists to be.

220
00:14:49,062 --> 00:14:52,456
And how powerful we were
and what we could achieve.

221
00:14:52,587 --> 00:14:57,984
He was one of the greatest
figures in American culture.

222
00:14:58,114 --> 00:15:00,334
A singer, a giant of a man,

223
00:15:00,464 --> 00:15:02,814
an all American football player,

224
00:15:02,945 --> 00:15:05,295
phi beta kappa, law student,

225
00:15:05,426 --> 00:15:09,604
actor, shakespearean,
and a leader of his people.

226
00:15:09,734 --> 00:15:13,608
And so inspiring was he
and so powerful was he,

227
00:15:13,738 --> 00:15:18,787
that at all costs,
he had to be silenced.

228
00:15:18,918 --> 00:15:22,791
And as a matter of fact
on the agenda to silence him

229
00:15:22,922 --> 00:15:26,229
was the understanding
that if we can silence him,

230
00:15:26,360 --> 00:15:30,190
all others will come
far more easily.

231
00:15:30,277 --> 00:15:32,279
Paul was a threat because he

232
00:15:32,409 --> 00:15:37,458
was a tremendously intelligent
and well learned man.

233
00:15:37,588 --> 00:15:41,244
Paul also had charisma
in the same sense

234
00:15:41,375 --> 00:15:42,985
that Martin Luther King
had charisma,

235
00:15:43,116 --> 00:15:45,640
in other words Paul
was the kind of man

236
00:15:45,727 --> 00:15:47,947
that could lead
masses of people.

237
00:15:48,077 --> 00:15:50,253
And those who understand
those things

238
00:15:50,384 --> 00:15:52,125
knew that Paul robeson
was a man

239
00:15:52,212 --> 00:15:55,780
who could affect
large majorities.

240
00:15:55,911 --> 00:15:59,262
Now all this took place
in an atmosphere super heated

241
00:15:59,393 --> 00:16:04,311
by the relationships between
Russia and america at the time.

