00:29:15,579 --> 00:29:19,845
sent a letter to her asking
"is any of this true?"

490
00:29:19,975 --> 00:29:22,195
The agency tried very hard

491
00:29:22,325 --> 00:29:25,459
not to put anything in writing
about this whole system.

492
00:29:25,589 --> 00:29:29,071
They even corrupted the language
to take care of it.

493
00:29:29,202 --> 00:29:31,552
They didn't say
"he's not acceptable"

494
00:29:31,682 --> 00:29:33,772
they said "he's not available."

495
00:29:33,902 --> 00:29:35,121
In fact, her appearance
before the committee

496
00:29:35,251 --> 00:29:37,601
was at her request.

497
00:29:37,732 --> 00:29:40,648
She hadn't been subpoenaed,

498
00:29:40,779 --> 00:29:42,650
many people advised her
not to do it.

499
00:29:42,781 --> 00:29:45,653
She said this is a matter
where not only my career,

500
00:29:45,740 --> 00:29:52,442
but my name have been taken
and used improperly.

501
00:29:52,573 --> 00:29:59,145
Here you had someone who had had
her own network radio program

502
00:29:59,232 --> 00:30:01,060
from the early '40s, on.

503
00:30:01,190 --> 00:30:03,627
You had someone who was,
I believe,

504
00:30:03,758 --> 00:30:06,152
the first black headliner

505
00:30:06,282 --> 00:30:10,547
of a weekly network
television program,

506
00:30:10,678 --> 00:30:16,423
who appeared in movies regularly
and all that stopped,

507
00:30:16,553 --> 00:30:18,860
and it all stopped just after
the time of her appearance

508
00:30:18,991 --> 00:30:21,210
before the committee.

509
00:30:22,559 --> 00:30:25,345
It's important to remember
that this whole dreadful period

510
00:30:25,475 --> 00:30:28,609
happened at the very birth
of television.

511
00:30:28,696 --> 00:30:33,048
Television in its first years
lived in this atmosphere

512
00:30:33,135 --> 00:30:38,097
of backbiting and
defamation and fear,

513
00:30:38,227 --> 00:30:40,969
which I'm sure had an enormous
effect on its future.

514
00:30:41,100 --> 00:30:47,106
When I first discovered
the blacklist,

515
00:30:47,193 --> 00:30:49,804
I had gone to see my agent

516
00:30:49,935 --> 00:30:56,289
and it was about getting
a job in television.

517
00:30:56,376 --> 00:30:58,465
And he was an agent

518
00:30:58,595 --> 00:31:01,163
in one of the most powerful
agencies in america

519
00:31:01,294 --> 00:31:02,817
and I was just at the threshold

520
00:31:02,948 --> 00:31:06,777
of the launching
of my own career.

521
00:31:06,908 --> 00:31:13,741
And he pulled out a drawer in
his desk, reached for a phone,

522
00:31:13,872 --> 00:31:17,223
it was not part
of the regular phone bank,

523
00:31:17,353 --> 00:31:22,924
he dialed a number and all
he did was to give my name,

524
00:31:23,055 --> 00:31:27,624
Harry Belafonte, and then
he waited for instruction

525
00:31:27,711 --> 00:31:31,324
and then he hung up the phone,
closed the drawer,

526
00:31:31,454 --> 00:31:36,416
and said "you're on the list,
you're unemployable."

527
00:31:36,546 --> 00:31:39,941
We figured we would go crazy
if we tried to figure out

528
00:31:40,072 --> 00:31:42,813
whether we were blacklisted
because we were black

529
00:31:42,944 --> 00:31:44,380
or blacklisted
because we were red.

530
00:31:44,511 --> 00:31:48,776
Evening old scores
is what this was all about.

531
00:31:48,907 --> 00:31:54,129
Tradition was that, whoever won
the Tony award in the theater,

532
00:31:54,216 --> 00:31:57,872
was on the following Sunday
after the awards were given

533
00:31:57,959 --> 00:32:02,007
to appear on the most popular
television show in america,

534
00:32:02,094 --> 00:32:04,574
the ed Sullivan show.

535
00:32:04,705 --> 00:32:07,490
Ed Sullivan was rooted
in American journalism,

536
00:32:07,621 --> 00:32:09,797
he was a most powerful reporter.

537
00:32:09,928 --> 00:32:14,584
He and Walter winchell
and a host of journalists

538
00:32:14,715 --> 00:32:19,198
used their tabloids to become
supporters of the black list.

539
00:32:19,328 --> 00:32:22,462
And when my name came up
as the winner of the Tony award,

540
00:32:22,549 --> 00:32:26,857
he was told
that I was unacceptable

541
00:32:26,988 --> 00:32:31,601
and he then called me to come
and have an interview with him,

542
00:32:31,732 --> 00:32:33,125
and I went.

543
00:32:33,255 --> 00:32:34,778
And he said "you know,
there is some resistance

544
00:32:34,909 --> 00:32:37,042
to your coming
on the show because of..."

545
00:32:37,172 --> 00:32:40,697
And he read a list of things
that I had been accused of

546
00:32:40,828 --> 00:32:46,268
and I said to him that many of
the things on the list were true

547
00:32:46,399 --> 00:32:50,620
and other things
on the list were false.

548
00:32:50,751 --> 00:32:53,972
But I do not choose to identify
which is true and which is false

549
00:32:54,102 --> 00:32:57,062
because that is not
really the issue.

550
00:32:57,192 --> 00:33:01,501
The issue is
my right to privacy,

551
00:33:01,631 --> 00:33:05,461
my right to my beliefs
as an American citizen

552
00:33:05,548 --> 00:33:08,116
and that I was sorry that
I did not have the opportunity

553
00:33:08,247 --> 00:33:12,120
to appear on his show, I would
dearly have loved to do so,

554
00:33:12,251 --> 00:33:14,601
it would have meant a lot
to my career

555
00:33:14,688 --> 00:33:16,385
and I thanked him and I left.

556
00:33:16,516 --> 00:33:19,519
That evening I got a call
from the very same agent

557
00:33:19,649 --> 00:33:22,348
who had picked up the phone
in the other instance,

558
00:33:22,478 --> 00:33:27,962
to tell me that I was on
the ed Sullivan show.

559
00:33:28,093 --> 00:33:31,183
And that I should be prepared to
go to rehearsals that Saturday

560
00:33:31,313 --> 00:33:32,619
and that Sunday,

561
00:33:32,749 --> 00:33:35,926
and that I'd be on the air live
that same weekend.

562
00:33:36,057 --> 00:33:41,367
This fact and this act forever
took me off the blacklist.

563
00:33:41,497 --> 00:33:45,806
Just ed Sullivan's endorsement
alone gave me that relief.

564
00:33:45,936 --> 00:33:47,938
But what it did do

565
00:33:48,069 --> 00:33:51,507
was that it instantly raised
significant suspicion

566
00:33:51,594 --> 00:33:55,772
among my colleagues
that I had betrayed them

567
00:33:55,903 --> 00:33:57,470
because there was no way

568
00:33:57,600 --> 00:33:59,863
for me to have gotten on
the ed Sullivan show

569
00:33:59,950 --> 00:34:04,303
if I had not played
the betrayal game.

570
00:34:04,433 --> 00:34:10,483
And it was a very, very,
very difficult time for me.

571
00:34:10,613 --> 00:34:13,442
Down I went to CBS,
I'll never forget it,

572
00:34:13,529 --> 00:34:18,795
and I stood in the doorway
where the typewriters were

573
00:34:18,882 --> 00:34:20,710
and the producer was,

574
00:34:20,841 --> 00:34:22,103
and he said
"yes, what are you doing?"

575
00:34:22,234 --> 00:34:24,279
And he got up and he was in
his shirtsleeves

576
00:34:24,366 --> 00:34:26,847
and he said, "we don't have any
maid's roles."

577
00:34:26,977 --> 00:34:30,503
And I said "oh, I know, but I
thought maybe I would be allowed

578
00:34:30,633 --> 00:34:32,766
to read for the receptionist"

579
00:34:32,853 --> 00:34:37,162
and he drew himself up
with pure disgust, looked at me

580
00:34:37,249 --> 00:34:40,600
and said "when the day comes

581
00:34:40,730 --> 00:34:44,908
that we cast you people
in a receptionist role,

582
00:34:45,039 --> 00:34:47,563
I will turn over in my grave."

583
00:34:47,694 --> 00:34:53,656
The absence of black faces
on television's whole schedule

584
00:34:53,743 --> 00:34:55,745
is racism much more

585
00:34:55,876 --> 00:34:59,314
than any particular
racist remark might be.

586
00:34:59,401 --> 00:35:03,492
So the most serious kind
of racism is invisible.

587
00:35:03,623 --> 00:35:09,629
I must tell you
I was blacklisted.

588
00:35:09,759 --> 00:35:17,550
I was a little bit tired
of seeing black actors in radio,

589
00:35:17,680 --> 00:35:20,379
as well as television,
that had just come on the scene,

590
00:35:20,509 --> 00:35:23,904
doing the kind of roles that
they were doing at all times.

591
00:35:23,991 --> 00:35:28,952
Now dick was one of those people
and still is,

592
00:35:29,083 --> 00:35:31,868
who always is aware
of what is going on

593
00:35:31,999 --> 00:35:33,435
and what ain't going on.

594
00:35:33,566 --> 00:35:35,698
And always takes
not only a position

595
00:35:35,829 --> 00:35:37,874
but something in the back of
his mind always pushes dick

596
00:35:38,005 --> 00:35:39,746
to do something about it.

597
00:35:39,876 --> 00:35:44,620
So I set up a campaign
in the negro press.

598
00:35:44,751 --> 00:35:48,363
I wrote articles and I put out
release after release,

599
00:35:48,494 --> 00:35:52,324
complaining and protesting
against the type of roles

600
00:35:52,454 --> 00:35:55,370
that black actors were
portraying in television

601
00:35:55,457 --> 00:35:57,764
and on radio
and everywhere else.

602
00:35:57,894 --> 00:36:04,597
And dick, as a part of being
dick Campbell, on one occasion,

603
00:36:04,727 --> 00:36:10,385
since there were no blacks
in television, called on Harlem

604
00:36:10,516 --> 00:36:15,042
to turn off the television set
on Saturday night.

605
00:36:15,173 --> 00:36:18,567
I said "don't turn on your TV,
leave it black

606
00:36:18,698 --> 00:36:21,266
because that's the only way
you can make the producers

607
00:36:21,396 --> 00:36:23,311
understand that you want

608
00:36:23,442 --> 00:36:26,401
a different type of show
on television.

609
00:36:26,532 --> 00:36:28,534
So don't turn it on."
They said "why not turn it on?"

610
00:36:28,664 --> 00:36:32,538
Because if you don't turn on
your television

611
00:36:32,625 --> 00:36:35,976
the commercial producers will
know that the products are not

612
00:36:36,106 --> 00:36:40,459
being sold to the audience
because ten percent

613
00:36:40,546 --> 00:36:45,290
of the population of the united
states that owns television sets

614
00:36:45,420 --> 00:36:48,728
are not watching,
so they will be losing money.

615
00:36:48,858 --> 00:36:50,730
That's what it's all about.

616
00:36:50,860 --> 00:36:53,994
So boycott on this
particular night.

617
00:36:54,124 --> 00:36:56,257
And we set up the boycott
and it worked.

618
00:36:56,388 --> 00:36:59,652
So then that's when
they called me downtown.

619
00:36:59,739 --> 00:37:02,916
I was surprised that the powers
that be were so disturbed

620
00:37:03,003 --> 00:37:06,702
but when they heard dick
calling for everybody,

621
00:37:06,833 --> 00:37:08,530
they said
"oh no, we must do something."

622
00:37:08,617 --> 00:37:12,491
And on the basis of that,
dick was sent for,

623
00:37:12,621 --> 00:37:15,058
and he talked and he negotiated,

624
00:37:15,189 --> 00:37:17,931
and he opened some doors
and got US some jobs.

625
00:37:18,018 --> 00:37:21,064
Of course,
they never gave dick a job.

626
00:37:21,195 --> 00:37:22,805
But here's what you have
to remember,

627
00:37:22,936 --> 00:37:27,549
every role I played,
I was a maid,

628
00:37:27,636 --> 00:37:31,031
I was either
the head housekeeper,

629
00:37:31,161 --> 00:37:34,121
or I was the nursemaid
for the family,

630
00:37:34,252 --> 00:37:37,994
or I was the janitor
or the day worker.

631
00:37:38,125 --> 00:37:39,953
Those were the roles.

632
00:37:40,083 --> 00:37:45,088
In my opinion, stereotypes
are not inherently offensive.

633
00:37:45,219 --> 00:37:49,049
It is who uses the stereotype
and to what end.

634
00:37:49,179 --> 00:37:53,401
In 1951 the naacp at
its convention condemned

635
00:37:53,532 --> 00:37:56,012
"Amos and Andy,"

636
00:37:56,143 --> 00:37:57,927
and in general people
were very surprised at that.

637
00:37:58,058 --> 00:38:00,408
How can they condemn
"Amos and Andy?"

638
00:38:00,539 --> 00:38:02,105
"Amos and Andy" had been,

639
00:38:02,236 --> 00:38:05,283
for years, and years, and years,
the number one program.

640
00:38:05,413 --> 00:38:09,330
Reportedly popular
in Harlem also.

641
00:38:09,461 --> 00:38:12,159
So why were they suddenly
complaining about it?

642
00:38:12,290 --> 00:38:16,511
So this opened a new discussion
about these symbols,

643
00:38:16,598 --> 00:38:18,121
these stereotypes.

644
00:38:18,252 --> 00:38:19,732
What in the world
am I going to do?

645
00:38:19,862 --> 00:38:21,995
This ain't no joke, son.

646
00:38:22,082 --> 00:38:24,693
I know, I'll go see
my lawyer Calhoun.

647
00:38:24,824 --> 00:38:27,696
Kingfish, the thing
for you to do

648
00:38:27,827 --> 00:38:30,960
is have your wife, sapphire,
go down to the draft board

649
00:38:31,047 --> 00:38:33,006
and plead with them
not to take you.

650
00:38:33,136 --> 00:38:34,312
Plead with them?

651
00:38:34,399 --> 00:38:37,445
That's what I said,
plead with them.

652
00:38:37,532 --> 00:38:41,536
Mister, you can't take
my husband to the army.

653
00:38:41,667 --> 00:38:45,497
You can't do it, he's all
I've got in the world,

654
00:38:45,627 --> 00:38:49,109
all I've got between me
and starvation.

655
00:38:49,196 --> 00:38:51,546
And what will become of
our three little children?

656
00:38:51,677 --> 00:38:54,201
Whose gonna take care
of little Dorothy,

657
00:38:54,332 --> 00:38:57,770
and Peggy,
and little erma?

658
00:38:57,900 --> 00:39:00,816
You can't take him,
not my man!"

659
00:39:00,903 --> 00:39:05,255
Being a fool or being silly gave
the whites a chance to justify

660
00:39:05,386 --> 00:39:08,302
a certain stereotype,
so we in the black community

661
00:39:08,433 --> 00:39:11,479
had to hold our artists
to a higher standard

662
00:39:11,610 --> 00:39:15,265
because they affected how we
were treated out in the world.

663
00:39:15,396 --> 00:39:22,272
We had an organization that was
sort of fighting the practice

664
00:39:22,403 --> 00:39:28,104
of the use that they were making
of negro actors at the time,

665
00:39:28,191 --> 00:39:32,021
and this was the case
of "Amos and Andy."

666
00:39:32,152 --> 00:39:37,070
We had particularly objected
to the way they described

667
00:39:37,157 --> 00:39:42,292
the lawyer and we asked
that this be changed

668
00:39:42,423 --> 00:39:44,643
and they made that change,

669
00:39:44,773 --> 00:39:48,211
but he was just a petty
politician instead of a lawyer

670
00:39:48,342 --> 00:39:51,693
because this gave
the wrong impression

671
00:39:51,824 --> 00:39:58,744
of that particular profession
of legal representation.

672
00:39:58,874 --> 00:40:00,833
I know you compromise
on a number of things

673
00:40:00,920 --> 00:40:03,575
but you just don't compromise
on certain principles.

674
00:40:03,705 --> 00:40:07,579
And so I don't compromise
on principles.

675
00:40:07,709 --> 00:40:09,276
